The scope `test` indicates that the dependencies (binary files) are only used using maven&#39;s test phase. They are not delivered with the final target jar though. So if you run tests yourself (rather than letting maven do it), you&#39;d better leave the default runtime scope, as follows:

    &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.mockito&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;mockito-all&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;2.0.2-beta&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

The problem you have is easy to solve, if you obey [Mockito&#39;s basic mocking principles](https://site.mockito.org/):

  - **Do not mock types you don’t own**
  - **Don’t mock value objects**
  - Don’t mock everything
  - Show love with your tests!

Please be sure to read also the detailed explanations, why you should not [mock type[s] you don&#39;t own](https://github.com/mockito/mockito/wiki/How-to-write-good-tests#dont-mock-type-you-dont-own).

Teaser: Escpescially for collections or collection-related classes in the JVM it is not just enough to mock one method like you did with `next()`, a consistent mocking of `hasNext()` has also to be done to prevent bad awakenings. :-)

So your test shrinks together to something like:

    @Test
    public void update() {
        Iterator i = List.of(&quot;Hello&quot;, &quot;World&quot;).iterator();
        String result = i.next() + &quot; &quot; + i.next();
        assertEquals(&quot;Hello World&quot;, result);
    }

If you read further in the [detailed docs](https://static.javadoc.io/org.mockito/mockito-core/2.25.1/org/mockito/Mockito.html), Section _&quot;1. Let&#39;s verify some behaviour!&quot;_ says:

