Some issues:

* The code creates a new node, assigns it to `newNode`, and then immediately assigns `temp` to `newNode`, thereby losing the reference to the newly created node

* `temp` is initialised with the value of `head`, then `newNode` gets the value of `temp` and then `head` gets the value of `temp`. This means you have set `head` to ... `head`, a no-operation.

* The loop performs `temp = head.next;` in each iteration. This will always put the *same* reference in `temp`... every time it executes. So the number of iterations of the loop becomes irrelevant. `temp` will always refer to the second node in the list. It would make more sense to do `temp = temp.next`

* In the last iteration you set `head.next = newNode;` ... even ignoring what you did with `temp`. This assignment uses nothing that was done during the iterations of the loop. It might as well be executed outside of the loop.

* The last statement `newNode = temp` is doing nothing useful. `newNode` is never used after that statement, so it might as well not be there. It would have made more sense if it were `newNode.next = temp`. That will effectively link `newNode` to a potentially next node.

* The loop iterates too many times. As you have used `pos == 0` to insert the new node at the start of the list, `pos == 1` should insert the new node after the `head` node, for which *no* iteration is necessary. Only when `pos &gt; 2` you need iteration(s).

Here is a corrected version:
```
public static SinglyLinkedListNode insert_at_position(SinglyLinkedListNode head, 
                                                      int val, int pos) {        
    SinglyLinkedListNode newNode = new SinglyLinkedListNode(val);
    if (pos == 0) {
        newNode.next = head;
        head = newNode;
    } else if (pos &gt; 0) {
        SinglyLinkedListNode temp = head;
        for (int i = 1; i &lt; pos; i++) {
            temp = temp.next;
        }
        newNode.next = temp.next;
        temp.next = newNode;
    }
    return head;
}
```

